all the way into the 1920's and none

01:01:20.510 --> 01:01:22.800
of them ever got through.

01:01:22.800 --> 01:01:28.030
Now, what Murray worked really
hard on was in Louisiana,

01:01:28.030 --> 01:01:33.020
there was a grandfather's clause,
was part of their new constitution

01:01:33.020 --> 01:01:37.940
which was a way to suppress,
almost entirely the black vote.

01:01:37.940 --> 01:01:42.480
In their constitution called
for a literacy requirement.

01:01:42.480 --> 01:01:49.340
But, they said that if anyone
was the descendent of the man

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:54.190
who could vote in 1865,
then they were exempt.

01:01:54.190 --> 01:01:56.110
They were grandfathered out.

01:01:56.110 --> 01:02:02.440
Well, that was, I mean obviously,
that's such an obvious way

01:02:02.440 --> 01:02:07.940
of getting around the intent of
the 15th amendment and Murray

01:02:07.940 --> 01:02:15.480
and the other officers in the
NAAC, took this on and as I say,

01:02:15.480 --> 01:02:16.780
it was the first time

01:02:16.780 --> 01:02:20.650
that a national civil rights
organizations said let's fight it

01:02:20.650 --> 01:02:21.950
out in the course.

01:02:21.950 --> 01:02:24.950
They didn't get as far as the
Supreme Court on a technicality,

01:02:24.950 --> 01:02:27.430
but they certainly
lead the groundwork

01:02:27.430 --> 01:02:30.950
for that approach in the future.

